	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=3&mid=99401966773575>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99401966773575>RE: Information</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=99401966773575#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sun, Jul 1st 4:34 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=39551><span id=Guru>Osano</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>171 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.44]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Yeah, I've seen some folks try and equate AC to HP too.&nbsp;&nbsp;It's a nearly impossible thing to make into a formula though, I think.  The way I look at it is that BOTH are health buffers; however, AC is a LIMITED health buffer in that it only protects from physical attack, whereas HP is a UNIVERSAL health buffer in that it protects from physical or magical attack.  For higher level situations, where you're pulling more casting MOBs, or fighting (not tanking) in a group against AoE casters, the HP is actually much more valuable than the AC.  Anyway, I think the earrings are a pretty clear upgrade from cougar-claw, whatever the reasoning.<br><br>And yes, I *do* think there is something about monks and enchanters.  Both classes fulfill key, and interesting, group functions, while at the same time they are very different to actually play.  They also both require some thought and work -- the monk with his variety of skills, the enchanter with his wide range of spell choices.  Thus, for someone who wants a break from a monk, but still wants interesting play-value, and to be desired for groups, the enchanter seems a logical choice.</p>&nbsp;<br>Osano<br>Level 44 Human Monk<br>Tholuxe-Paells</td></td></tr>
